definition.value: A 1,2-diacyl-sn-glycero-3-phosphocholine in which the two acyl substituents at positions 1 and 2 are specified as palmitoyl and propionyl respectively.
A 1,2-diacyl-sn-glycero-3-phosphocholine in which the two acyl substituents at positions 1 and 2 are specified as palmitoyl and butanoyl respectively.
A 1,2-diacyl-sn-glycero-3-phosphocholine in which the two acyl substituents at positions 1 and 2 are specified as palmitoyl and valeroyl respectively.
A potassium salt having sorbate as the counterion.
A sorbate obtained by deprotonation of the carboxy group of (E,E)-sorbic acid.
A boron-containing macrolide antibiotic that is isolated from Streptomyces antibioticus.
A 1,2-diacyl-sn-glycero-3-phosphocholine having palmitoyl and 5-oxovaleryl groups at the 1- and 2-positions respectively; major species at pH 7.3.

A macrolide antibiotic that is a semisynthetic analogue of concanamycin A, possessing an 18-membered lactone ring and a 6-membered oxane ring in which the hydroxy group at position 23 is glycosylated by a 4-O-carbamoyl-2,6-dideoxy-beta-D-arabino-hexopyranosyl residue.
An organic phosphate that is phosphoric acid in which one of the hydrogens is replaced by an organyl group.
A 1,2-diacyl-sn-glycerol 3-diphosphate in which both of the phosphatidyl acyl groups are specified as octanoyl.
A phosphocholine that is the monododecyl ester of phosphocholine
An organic chloride salt having 2,3,5-triphenyltetrazolium as the counterion.
A 1,2-diacyl-sn-glycero-3-phosphocholine in which the two acyl substituents at positions 1 and 2 are specified as stearoyl and alpha-linolenoyl respectively.
A hydrate that is the monohydrate of the hydrochloride salt of mitoguazone.
An inorganic nitrate salt having copper(2+) as the couterion.
Bacteria-synthesized intracellularly accumulated polyesters from saturated and unsaturated hydroxyalkanoic acid
An aminobenzoic acid that is anthranilic acid in which the hydrogen at position 5 on the phenyl ring is replaced by fluorine.
A 1-oleoyl-2-acyl-sn-glycero-3-phosphocholine in which the acyl substituent at position 2 is specified as acetyl.
A 2-acyl-sn-glycero-3-phosphocholine in which the acyl group at position 2 is specified as acetyl.
A fatty acid anion containing 18 carbons and one double bond. Formed by deprotonation of the carboxylic acid group. Major species at pH 7.3.
An inorganic chloride that has formula Cl2Sn.
A hydrate that is tin dichloride (anh.) combined with 2 mol eq. of water.
A penicillin antibiotic carrying a 5-methyl-3-phenylisoxazole-4-carboxamide group at position 6.
A 2-acetyl-1-alkyl-sn-glycero-3-phosphocholine in which the alkyl group is specified as tetradecyl.
A 1-alkyl-sn-glycero-3-phosphocholine in which the alkyl group is specified as tetradecyl.
A 2-acetyl-1-alkyl-sn-glycero-3-phosphocholine in which the alkyl group is specified as dodecyl.
A 1-alkyl-sn-glycero-3-phosphocholine in which the alkyl group is specified as dodecyl.
A 2-acetyl-1-alkyl-sn-glycero-3-phosphocholine in which the alkyl group is specified as decyl.
A 1-alkyl-sn-glycero-3-phosphocholine in which the alkyl group is specified as decyl.
Any saturated fatty acid anion containing 3 carbons. Formed by deprotonation of the carboxylic acid moiety. Major species at pH 7.3.
Any saturated fatty acid anion containing 4 carbons. Formed by deprotonation of the carboxylic acid moiety. Major species at pH 7.3.
Any saturated fatty acid anion containing 6 carbons. Formed by deprotonation of the carboxylic acid moiety. Major species at pH 7.3.
Any saturated fatty acid anion containing 12 carbons. Formed by deprotonation of the carboxylic acid moiety. Major species at pH 7.3.
A member of the class of bleomycins that is used in sclerotherapy for cervicofacial lymphatic malformations.
An alkylacylglycero-3-phosphocholine in which the alkyl and acyl groups are located at positions 1 and 2 respectively. Major species at pH 7.3.
A glycerophosphocholine that is glycero-3-phosphocholine carrying unspecified alk-1-enyl and acyl groups at positions 1 and 2 respectively. Major species at pH 7.3.
A glycerophosphocholine that is glycero-3-phosphocholine carrying one alkyl and one acyl group in unspecified positions. Major species at pH 7.3.
Any member of the class of lysophosphatidylcholines which has a free hydroxy group at the 2-position of the glycerol moiety.
Any member of the class of lysophosphatidylcholines which has a free hydroxy group at the 1-position of the glycerol moiety.
A monoalkylglycerophosphocholine in which the alkyl group may be attached to the sn-1 or sn-3 position.
A glycerophosphocholine that is glycero-3-phosphocholine bearing a single alkenyl group located at position 1.
A glycerophosphocholine that is glycero-3-phosphocholine bearing a single alkyl substituent at an unspecified position (sn-1, sn-2, or sn-3).
A dicarboxylic acid dianion obtained by deprotonation of both carboxy groups of of azelaic acid; major species at pH 7.3.
A 1-O-acyl-sn-glycero-3-phosphocholine in which the acyl group is specified as caproyl (hexanoyl).
An organic phosphonate that is phenylphosphonic acid diesterified with tropinium and 4-nitrophenol.
A 1,2-diacyl-sn-glycero-3-phosphocholine in which the acyl groups at positions 1 and 2 are specified as capryl (decanoyl).
A 1,2-diacyl-sn-glycero-3-phosphocholine in which the acyl groups at positions 1 and 2 are specified as octanoyl.
A hydroxybenzaldehyde that is 4-hydroxybenzaldehyde bearing an additional amino substituent at position 3.
A sphingomyelin in which the ceramide N-acyl group is specified as hexanoyl.
